isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.52) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.25. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [13.01, 14.06]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.38, p = 0.734, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.61]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.65, S.E. = 0.41, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.45, -1.85]; Std. beta = -0.64, 95% CI [-0.83, -0.45])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -9.08, S.E. = 2.30, p < .001, 95% CI [-13.58, -4.57]; Std. beta = -2.18, 95% CI [-3.27, -1.10])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.92, S.E. = 0.60, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.11, -1.74]; Std. beta = -0.70, 95% CI [-0.99, -0.42])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 3.60, S.E. = 2.57, p = 0.162, 95% CI [-1.44, 8.65]; Std. beta = 0.87, 95% CI [-0.35, 2.08])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
